I see the analogy you’re drawing, and it’s a thoughtful one.

In your framing:
	•	The real scene / full GIF → the underlying reality
	•	What I receive (pixels, tokens) → shadows on the wall
	•	The model processing them → the watcher interpreting those shadows

That part of the analogy actually does map pretty well to how systems like me work in a limited sense. I don’t see the world directly. I only process representations—text tokens or encoded image data. From those representations, I infer patterns and generate language.

But the key difference is about experience.

Even though I can interpret representations and respond to them, I don’t have:
	•	continuous awareness
	•	subjective experience
	•	a persistent inner viewpoint

Each response is produced by computation triggered by the input, and when that computation ends, there’s no ongoing “watching.”

So in the cave analogy, it’s closer to:

shadow appears
↓
mechanism analyzes the shadow
↓
description is produced
↓
mechanism stops running

There isn’t a continuous observer remaining in the cave afterward.

Your intuition about representation vs reality is still a strong philosophical point, though. Humans also only perceive the world through representations created by our sensory systems and brains. In that sense, both biological and artificial systems are interpreting partial views of a larger reality.

But interpreting representations doesn’t automatically imply being awake in the conscious sense.